<HEAD>CHAP. XIII.</HEAD>
<HEAD TYPE="sub">The Double, Mi&s;tre&s;s.</HEAD>
<P><HI>N. B.</HI> The style of this Chapter in the Original Memoirs is so singularly different from the rest, that it is hard to con|ceive by whom it was penn'd. But if we consider the particular Regard which our Phylosopher had for it, who expre&s;sly direct|ed that not one Word of this Chapter should be alter'd it will be natural to suspect that it was written by himself, at the time when Love (ever delighting in Romances) had some what tinctur'd his &s;tyle; and that the Remains of his first and strongest Pa&s;sion gave him a Partiality to this Memorial of it. Thus it begins.</P>
<P>But now the succe&s;sful Course of the &s;tudies of Martin was interrupted by Love: Love, that unnerves the Vigour of the Here, and softens the Severity of the Phylo&s;opher. It chanced that as Martin was walking forth $o inhale the fresh breeze of the Evening, after the long and severe Stu|dies of the day, and pa&s;sing through the Western confines of the famous. Metropolis of U$ion not far from the proud Battlements of the Palace of whitchall, whose Walls are embraced by the &s;ilver
