<P>The Sun had twice eight times perform'd his annual course, since their Mother brought them into the world with double Pangs. Lindamira's Eyes were of a lively blue; Indamera's were black and piercing.
<PB N="424" REF="431">
Lindamirds $heeks might riral the blush of the m$rning; in Indamera the Lilly evercame the Rose Lindamirds tre$s$s were of the paler Gold, while the locks of Indamera were black and gle$sy as the Plumes of a $aren.</P>
<P>$ow great is the power of Love in human breasts! In vain has the wise man recourse to his Reason, when the insinuating Arrow touches his Heart, and the pleasing Poison is diffus'd through his $$$ns. But then how violent, how transporting must that pa&s;sion $word$ where not only the Fire of youth, but the unquenchable curiosity of a Phylosopher, pitch'd upon the same object! For how much s$ever our. Harlin was enamour'd on her as a beautiful Woman, he was infinitely more ra|$ish'd with her as a charming Monster. What wonder then, if his gentle Spirit, already humani$'d by a polite Education to receive all soft impre&s;sions, and fired by the sight of those beauties so lavishly expos'd to his view, should prove unable to resist at once so pleasing a Pa&s;sion, and so amiable a Phaenom$non?</P>
<P>Martin, who felt the true emotions of Love, blush'd that the object of his flame should be so openly prestituted to rulgar Eyes. And though he had been permitted to peruse her most secret Charms, yet his honourable Pa&s;sion was so strong, that it ran into the extreme of
<PB N="425" REF="432">
Bashfulne&s;s; so that at the first interview he made no $r$r$ur$s of his Love. Pensive he return'd, and flinging himself on his Couch, pa&s;s'd away the tedious hours of the Sight in the almost inquietude. The rushi$ taper afforded a glimm 'ring light, by which he contemplated the under lines of Orid; but alas! his remedy of $word$ was no $ur$ for our unhappy Lev$r's anxiety! $word$ closed the amorous volume, sigh'd, and casting his Eyes around on the Books that adorn'd his room, broke forth in this pathetic Apostrophe.</P>
<P>Eye Spirits of antiquity, who yet live in those sacred leaves! why do I make you conscious of my Shame? Yet why should I dipreciate th$ noble Pa&s;sion of Love, and call it Shame? your Heroes have felt it, your poets and Orators have prais'd it. Were I enamour'd on some gaudy $$$gin, did I deat on vulgar Perfection, the Lustre of an Eye, or the Rose of a Cheek; with reason might $ blush before you, most learned In quisiters into. Sature! most r$m rend Plony&punc; Elian, and Aldrovandus! Yet sure you cannot disapprove of this, which is no wanton pa&s;sion, but excited by so unparallel'd a Production; a flame, that may not only justify itself to the severity of a Phylosopher, but even to the avarice of a Parent; since she who causes it car|ries a most plentiful fortune in the sole Exhibition
<PB N="426" REF="433" MS="Y">
of her Person. Heavens! how Iwonder at the stupidity of mankind, who can affix the opprobrious name of Monstrosity to what is only variety of Beauty, and a profusion of Generous Nature&punc; If there are Charms in one Face, one mouth, one Body; if there are charms in two Eyes, two Breasts, two Arms; are they not all re|doubled in the object of my Pa&s;sion? What tho' sh$$$ the common gaze of the multitude, and is fellow'd about by the stupid and ignorant; does she not herein resemble the greatest Princes, and the greatest Beauties? only with this difference, that her admirers are more numerous, and more lasting.</P>
<P>Thus sigh'd he away the melancholy Night; but no sooner had Aurora, with blushes in her cheeks as conscious that she was just risen from the embraces of Tithon) advanc'd through the purple gates of the East, $word$ Martin r$se: He ros$ indeed but melancholy, the companion of his Numbers rose and mak'd with him. This was the first day that he amused himself with the gaudy ornaments of the Body; that with secret pleasure he contemplated his Face, and the Symmetry of his Limbs in a Looking-gla&s;s. And now forsaking his solitary apartment, he walk'd directly to the habitation that confin'd the object of his Desires.</P>
