<HEAD>D^r. Penny-feather.</HEAD>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;I appear before your Honour in behalf of Martinus Scri|blerus, Batchelor of Physick, in a Complaint against Ebn-Hai-Paw-W$w, commonly call'd the black Prince of Mene|m$tapa; Inasmuch as the said Ebn-Hai-Paw-W$w, hath maliciously, forcibly, and unlawly seiz'd ravish'd, and detain'd Lindamira-Indamora, the Wife of the said. Martin, and the Body of the said Lindamira-Indamora from time to time ever since, hath wickedly, l$wdly, and
<PB N="443" REF="450">
indecently us'd, handled, and $rib entreated. And in or|der to make this his $ill any more lasting, hath presum'd to marry this our Wife, pretending to give his wickedne&s;s the Sanction of a Saw. And forasmuch as the adulterer&punc; doth not d$ny the fact, but insists upon his said marriage as lawful, we cannot open the Case more plainly to your Honour, than by answering his Reasons, which, indeed to mention, is to cenful$.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;He maintains nole&s;s an absurdity than this, that One is Two; and that Lindamira-Indamora, the indivi|dual wife of the Plaintiff, is not one, but two Persons: and that the said Ebn-Hai-Paw-Waw is not married to Lin|damira, the Wife of the said. Martin, but to his own lawful Wife Indamora, another individual person distinct from the said Lindamira, the join'd to her by a strong Ligament of Nature.</Q></P>
<P>In answer whereunto we shall prove three things: <Q>&startq;&endq;First, that the said Lindamira-Indamora, now our lawful Wife makes but one individual Person.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;Secondly, That if they made two individual Persons, yet they constitute but one Wife.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;Thirdly, That supposing they made two individual Per|sons,
<PB N="444" REF="451" MS="Y">
and $word$ Hives each lawfully marry'd to her own $word$ band, yet Prince Ebn-Hai-Paw-$$$$ hath no right to detain Lindamira our lawful wedded wife, on pretence of being married to Indamora.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;As to the first point: It will be nece&s;sary to determine the constituent Principle and E$$$nce of Individuality, which, in respect to mankind, we take to be one &s;imple identical $$ul in one simple Identical Body. The individuality, samene&s;s or identity of the body, is not determin'd (as some vainly imagine) by one head, and a certain number of arms, legs, and other mem|bers; but in one simple <GAP DESC="FOREIGN"> or member of Generation&punc; Let us search profane History, and we shall find Geryon with three heads, and Briar$$s with an Hundred hands. Let us search sacred History, and we meet with one of the Sons of the Giants with &s;ix Fingers to each hand, and six $$$s to each Foot; yet none ever accounted Ge|ryon or Briar$us more than one Person: and give us leave to say, the wife of the said Geryon would have had a good action against any women who should have espous'd themselves to the other two heads of that Monarch. The Reason is plain; because each of these having but
<PB N="445" REF="452" MS="Y">
one simple <GAP DESC="FOREIGN">, or one Member of Generation, could be look'd upon as but one single Person.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;In conformity to this, when we behold this one Member, we distinguish the Sex, and pronounce it a Man, or a Woman; or as the $alins expre&s;s it, $word$ and $word$ an Homme, $word$ F$mme; one Man, one Woman. For the same Reason. Man and Wife are said to be one Fle$$$ because united in that part which constitutes the samene&s;s and individuality of each Sex.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;And as there is but one Member of Generation, there is but one Body, so there can be but one Soul; because the said&punc; Organ of Generation is the Seat of the Soul; and conse|quently, where there is but one such Organ, there can be but one Soul. Set me here say, without injury to truth, that no Phylosopher, either of the past or present age, hath taken more pains to discover where the Soul keeps her residence, than the Plaintiff, the learned Martinus S$ribl$rus: And after his most diligent enquiries and experiments, he hath been verily p$rs$aded, that the Organ of Generation is the true and only Seal of the Soul. That this part is seated in the middle, and near the Centre of the whole Body, is obvious to your Honour's
<PB N="446" REF="453">
view. From thence, like the Sun in the Centre of the World, the $eal dispenses her warmth and vital influenc$&punc; $$t the Brain glory in the Wisdom of the aged, the Science of the learned, the policy of the Statesman, and the In|$ention of the witty; the accidental Amusements and $word$ of the Soul, and mortal as the $word$ of them&punc; It is to the $r$an$ of Generation that we awe man himself&punc; there the Soul is employ'd in works Suitable to the dignity of her nature, and (as we may $word$ oils breeding over ages yet unborn.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;We need not tell your Honour, that it has been the opini|on of many most learned $irines and Phylosephers, that the S$ul, as well as Body, is produced $word$ traduc$. This d$ct$ine has been defended by arguments irrefraga$$, and accounts for difficulties, without it, inexplicable. All which arguments conclude with equall strength, for the Soul's being seated in the organs of Generation. For since the whole Man, both Soul and Body, is there form'd, and since nothing can operate but where it is, it follows, that the Soul must reside in that individual place, where She exerts her generatir$ and plastic pow|ers.</Q></P>
<P><PB N="447" REF="454">
<Q>&startq;&endq;This our doctrine is confirm'd by all these Experiments, which conspire to prove the absolute dominion which that part hath over the whole Body. We see how ma|ny women, who are deaf to the persuasions of the Elo|quent, the insinuations of the Crafty, and the threats of the imperious, are easily governed by some poor $word$ unfurnish'd with the least art, but that of making immediate application to this Seat of the Soul. The impre&s;sions made by the Ear are so distant, and transmitted thro' so many windings, that they lose their Energy: But your honour, by immediately applying to the organ of generation, gets like a bold and wise Petitioner, who goes strait to the very throne and Judgment-Seal of the Monarch. And whereas it is objected that here are two Wills, and therefore $word$ different persons; we answer, if multi|plicity of Wills implied multiplicity of Persons, there are few Husbands but what are guilty of Polygamy, there being in the same woman great and notorious diversi|ty of Wills: A point which we shall not need to insist upon before any married person, much le&s;s of your Honour's Experience.</Q></P>
<P><PB N="448" REF="455">
<Q>&startq;&endq;Thus we have made $eed our first and principal point; That if the Wife of the Plaintiff, Lindamira-Indamora, hath but one Organ of Generation, she is but one individual Person, in the truest and most proper Sense of Individuality. And that the matter of Sad is so, we are willing to put up on a fair Trial by a $ury of $atrons, whom year Honour shall think fit to nominate and appoint, to inspect the Body of the said Lindamira-Indamora.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;Secondly, We are to prove, that tho' Lindamira-Indamora were two individual Persons, consisting each of a Soul and Body, yet, if they have but one Organ of Generation, they can constitute but one Wi$e. $or, from whence can the Unity of any thing be denominated, but from that which constitutes the E&s;sence or principal use of it? Thus, if a knife or hatche$ have but one blade, though two handles, it will properly be denominated but one knife, $word$ hatche$; in as much as it hath but one of that which constitutes the E&s;sence or principal Use of a knife or hatche$. So if there were not only one, but twenty Supposita Rationalia with one common Organ of Generation, that one System would only make
<PB N="449" REF="456">
one Wife. Upon the whole, let not a few heads, legs, or arms extraordinary, bia$s your Honour's Judgment, and de|prive the Plaintiff of his legal property: In which right our Client is so strongly fortified, that allowing both the former Prepositions to be false, and that there were two persons, two Bodies, two Rational Souls, yea, and two Organs of Generation, yet would it still be plain in the third place.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;That the Defendant, Prince Ebn-Hai-Pa$-Wa$, can have no Right to detain from the Plaintiff his lawfully wedded Wife, Lindamira. For, abstracting from the priority of the marriage of our Client, by which it would seem he acquired a property in his Wife and all other matter inseparably anner'd unto her, it is evident Prince Ebn-Hai-Paw-Waw, by his Marriage to Indamora, could never acquire any property in Lindamira; nor can produce any Cause why both of them should live with himself, rather than with the other? Therefore, we humbly hope your Honour will order the Body of our said Wife to be restored to us, and due Censure past on the said Ebn-Hai-Paw-Waw.</Q></P>
<P><PB N="450" REF="457">
