<P><Q>&startq;&endq;I will not trouble your Honour with any unnece$sary Preamble, or false $$lours of Elequence, which truth $word$ no need of, and which would prove too thin a $word$ for Falshood before the penetrating Eyes of your Honour. In answer therefore to what our learned brother, Dr. Pennyfeather, hath a$serted, we shall labour to demonstrate,</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;First, That though there were but one Organ of Generation, yet are there two distinct persons. Secondly, That, although there were but one Organ of Generation, so far would it be from giving the Plaintiff any right to the Body of Indamora, the Wife of Ebn-$ai-Pa$-W$$, that it will subject the Plaintiff to the Penalty of $n$$st, or of Bigamy.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;Thirdly, We doubt not to prove that the said Lin|damira-Indamora hath two distinct parts of Generation. And, first we will show, that neither the individual $$sence of Mankind, nor the seat of the Soul, doth re|side in the Organ of Generation; and this first
<PB N="451" REF="458" MS="Y">
from Reason. For unreasonable indeed must it be, to make that the Seat of the rational Soul, which alone sets us on a level with beasts; or to conceive, that the E$sence of unity and individuality should consist in that which is the source of Discord and Division. In a word, what can be greater absurdity, than to affirm $$stiality to be the E&s;sence of Humanity, Darkne&s;s the Centre of Light, and $il$hine&s;s the Seat of Purity? We could, from the authority of the most eminent Phi|losophers of allages, confirm this our A&s;sertion: few of whom ever had the Impudence to degrade this $$een, the rational Soul, to the very lowest and $ilest apartment, or rather Sink of her whole Palace. But we shall produce still a greater Authority than these, to manifest that personal Individuality did subsist, when there was no such generative Carnality.</Q></P>
<P><Q>&startq;&endq;It hath been strenuously maintain'd by many ho|ly Divines and particularly by Thomas Aquinas that our first Parents, in the state of Innocence, did in no wise propagate their Species after the present common manner of men and beasts; but that the pro|pagation at that time must have been by Intuition,
<PB N="452" REF="459">
$word$ of Ideas, or some pure and spiritual manner, suitable to the dignity of their Station. And the $word$ were distinguish'd in that State, yet it is plain it was not by parts, such as we have at present; since if our first Parents had any such, they must have known it; and it is written, that they discover'd them $et till after the Fall; when it is probable those parts were the immediate Exere$cence of Sin, and only grow forth to render them fitter companions for those beasts among which they were driven.</Q></P>
<P>It is a maxim in Phylosophy, that generatio $$ius $st $word$ $$erius; whence it is apparent that the Pa|ra disaical Generation was of a different nature from ours, free from all corruption and Tr$becillity, This is farther $erreb$rated by the authority of those Doctors of the Church who have a&s;serted, that before the Fall, Adam was $ndew'd with a continual uninterrupted Faculty of Generation, which can be explain'd of $e other than of that Intuitire Ge|neration abovesaid: Since it is well known to all, the least skill'd in Anatomy, that the present (male) part of Generation is utterly incapable
<PB N="453" REF="460">
of this continual Faculty.</P>
<Q>&startq;&endq;We come new to our second point, wherein the ad|vocate for the plaintiff a $word$ that if there were two persons, and one Organ of Generation, this Sys|tem would constitute but one Wife. This will put the Plaintiff still in a worse Condition, and render him plainly guilty of Bigamy, Rap$, or Incest. For if there be but one such Organ of Generation then both the persons of Lindami$a and Indamera have an equal property in it, and what is Indamera's properly cannot be dispos'd of without her consent. We therefore bring the whole to this short I&s;sue; whether the Plaintiff. Martinus Scriblerus had the consent of Indamera, or not&punc; If he hath had her consent, he is guilty of Bigamy; if not, he is guilty of a Rape, or Incest, or both.</Q>
<Q>&startq;&endq;The Dependant, Prince $$n-Hai-$aw-Waw, having been lately baptiz'd; hath with singular medisty abstain'd from consummation with his said Wife, untill he shall be satisfied from the opinion of your Honour, his learned Judge, how far in Law and Conscience he may proceed; and therefore he&punc;
<PB N="454" REF="461">
cannot affirm much, nor positively, as to the structure of the Organ of Generation of this his Wife Indamera. Yet make we no doubt, that it will upon inspection appear, that the said Organ is distinct from that of $in|damira: whereupon we $word$ to hear the report of the jury of. $atrons&punc; appointed to inspect the Body of the said Gentlewoman.</Q>
<Q>&startq;&endq;And if the matter of $span$ give me your Honour's permi&s;sion to repeat what hath been said by the advo|cate for the Plaintiff; to wit, that Martinus Scriblerus, Batchelor in Physick, by this his Marriage with Linda|mira, could in no wise acquire any property in the Body of $ndamera, nor shew any Cause why this duplicated Wife Lindamira-Indamera, should abide with him, rather than with the Dependant, Prince E$n-Hai-$aw-$aw of $word$.</Q>
<P>The Jury of Matrons having made their Report, and it appearing from thence that the parts of Generation in Lindamira and Indamera were distinct, the Judge $word$ time to deliberate, and the next Court-day he spoke to this effect.</P>
