<P>But we must not here neglect to mention, that du|ring the whole course of this proce&s;s, his c$ntinual Attendance on the Courts in his own Cause, and his invincible Curiosity for all that past in the Causes of others, gave him a Wonderful insight into this branch of Learning, which must be confe&s;s'd to have been so improved by the Moderns, as beyond all Comparison to exceed the ancients. From the day his first Bill was filed, he began to collect Reports; and before his Suit was ended, he had time abundantly sufficient to complite a very considerable Column. His anger
